    q: "A nurse is caring for a client with lung cancer who develops a serum calcium of 14.2 mg/dL (normal 8.5-10.5 mg/dL). The client reports confusion, constipation, excessive thirst, and muscle weakness. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate first?",
    o: ["Restrict fluid intake to prevent further calcium concentration in the blood", "Initiate aggressive IV normal saline hydration and prepare to administer IV bisphosphonates as ordered", "Administer calcium supplements to correct the imbalance", "Encourage weight-bearing activity to force calcium back into the bones"],
    a: 1,
    r: "Hypercalcemia of malignancy occurs when tumors produce parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP) or when bone metastases release calcium, and is most common in lung, breast, and multiple myeloma cancers. A calcium of 14.2 mg/dL is severe and can cause fatal cardiac dysrhythmias, renal failure, and coma. The first intervention is aggressive IV normal saline hydration (200-500 mL/hour initially) to restore intravascular volume and promote renal calcium excretion. Once hydrated, IV bisphosphonates (zoledronic acid or pamidronate) inhibit osteoclast activity and reduce bone resorption of calcium. Fluid restriction would concentrate calcium further. Additional calcium is dangerous and contraindicated. While weight-bearing helps prevent osteoporosis, it does not acutely lower serum calcium in malignancy-related hypercalcemia.",
